sentences: Bayer Leevince Mack (born August 26, 1972) is an American record executive and filmmaker.
In 1999, Mack signed an affiliate contract with the AKA.com Hip-Hop Network created by Loud Records founder Steve Rifkind.
Mack became the marketing manager of a German hip-hop website called YoRaps.com in 2008.
Mack made his directorial debut in 2014 with the documentary film Oscar Micheaux: The Czar of Black Hollywood.

In 2019, Mack wrote and directed a documentary film on the rise and decline of the black-owned ethnic beauty industry, called No Lye: An American Beauty Story.
Mack's film Black Seeds: The History of Africans in America won the "Best Feature Documentary" award and a $20,000 camera package from Panavision at the 2021 Denton Black Film Festival.
In an April 2014 interview with The Washington Times, Mack said he was inspired to produce a film about Oscar Micheaux's life because it mirrored his own.
Mack attended Central Middle School (now Central Magnet School) and Oakland High School.
